Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>
#include <map>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt"); // replace with your file name
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string word;
    std::map<std::string, int> wordCount;
    int lineCount = 0;

    while (std::getline(file, word)) {
        ++lineCount;
        std::istringstream iss(word);
        std::string token;
        while (std::getline(iss, token, ' ')) {
            ++wordCount[token];
        }
    }

    file.close();

    std::cout << "Word count:" << std::endl;
    for (const auto& pair : wordCount) {
        std::cout << pair.first << ": " << pair.second << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
Here's how the program works:

1. We open the file using an `ifstream` object.
2. We read the file line by line using `std::getline`.
3. For each line, we split the line into individual words using `std::istringstream` and a space character as the delimiter.
4. We count the occurrences of each word using a `std::map` to store the word as the key and the count as the value.
5. We print the word count to the console.

Note that this program is case-sensitive, so if you want to ignore case, you can convert the words to lowercase or uppercase before counting them.

Also, this program assumes that the file is in the same directory as the executable. If the file is in a different directory, you'll need to specify the full path to the file.

You can replace `"example.txt"` with the name of your text file.
